{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:50:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.21,0.63,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7053"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40358"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"3620"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4399"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16785"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is admitted to the labour ward at 38 weeks gestation with her first pregnancy. She has a history of gestational hypertension diagnosed at 36 weeks. On admission, her blood pressure is 160/100 mmHg. Her urine protein to creatinine ratio is 45 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;30). She receives two 1L boluses of intravenous normal saline over four hours for concerns with fetal CTG and fluid pre-loading prior to an epidural. Labour is induced. Fetal CTG normalises and she is started on an oxytocin infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 135 g/L (110-150)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count: 150 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EALT: 65 U/L (5-40)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 95 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is this patient at greatest risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chorioamnionitis","Sheehan syndrome","Pulmonary oedema","Pulmonary fibrosis","Peripartum Cardiomyopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with pre-eclampsia who has received multiple fluid boluses and is on an oxytocin infusion is at greatest risk of developing \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E. Pre-eclampsia itself predisposes patients to pulmonary oedema due to increased capillary permeability and decreased colloid oncotic pressure. The risk is significantly increased by excessive fluid administration and the use of oxytocin, which has an antidiuretic effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChorioamnionitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the fetal membranes and amniotic fluid. While it can occur during labour, there are no signs of infection mentioned in this scenario, and the risk is not increased by fluid administration or pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESheehan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition of hypopituitarism caused by severe postpartum haemorrhage. While pre-eclampsia can increase the risk of postpartum haemorrhage, Sheehan syndrome is not an immediate concern in this intrapartum scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic, progressive lung disease characterized by scarring of lung tissue. It is not an acute complication of pregnancy or pre-eclampsia and is unrelated to fluid administration or oxytocin use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripartum Cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare form of heart failure that occurs during the last month of pregnancy or up to five months after delivery. While it\u0027s a serious condition, it\u0027s not directly related to fluid overload or pre-eclampsia in the way that pulmonary oedema is.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of pre-eclampsia, multiple fluid boluses, and oxytocin infusion significantly increases the risk of pulmonary oedema. Oxytocin has an antidiuretic effect, which can exacerbate fluid retention. In pre-eclampsia, there\u0027s already a tendency towards third-spacing of fluids due to endothelial dysfunction. The additional fluid load from IV boluses and the fluid-retaining effects of oxytocin create an ideal scenario for pulmonary oedema to develop. Careful fluid management and vigilant monitoring for signs of pulmonary oedema are crucial in managing such patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary oedema is a serious complication of pre-eclampsia, especially when excessive intravenous fluids are administered.","Careful fluid management is crucial in pre-eclamptic patients, with a preference for controlled infusion over boluses.","Oxytocin infusion can exacerbate fluid retention and increase the risk of pulmonary oedema in pre-eclamptic patients."],"references":["Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Guidelines for the management of hypertensive disorders of pregnancy. Melbourne: SOMANZ; 2015. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2020/07/HTguidelineupdatedJune2015.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40358"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-10T17:36:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T17:37:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7053"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1177"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"FBE","synonyms":["Full blood exam","Complete blood count","CBC","CBE","Complete blood evaluation","C